# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ccd-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] A **charge-coupled device** (**CCD**) is an integrated circuit containing an array of linked, or coupled, capacitors.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Under the control of an external circuit, each capacitor can transfer its electric charge to a neighboring capacitor.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] CCD sensors are a major technology used in digital imaging.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In a CCD image sensor, pixels are represented by p-doped metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) capacitors.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] These MOS capacitors, the basic building blocks of a CCD, are biased above the threshold for inversion when image acquisition begins, allowing the conversion of incoming photons into electron charges at the semiconductor-oxide interface; the CCD is then used to read out these charges.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Although CCDs are not the only technology to allow for light detection, CCD image sensors are widely used in professional, medical, and scientific applications where high-quality image data are required.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In applications with less exacting quality demands, such as consumer and professional digital cameras, active pixel sensors, also known as CMOS sensors (complementary MOS sensors), are generally used.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] However, the large quality advantage CCDs enjoyed early on has narrowed over time and since the late 2010s CMOS sensors are the dominant technology, having largely if not completely replaced CCD image sensors.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The basis for the CCD is the metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) structure, with MOS capacitors being the basic building blocks of a CCD, and a depleted MOS structure used as the photodetector in early CCD devices.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In the late 1960s, Willard Boyle and George E.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Smith at Bell Labs were researching MOS technology while working on semiconductor bubble memory.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] They realized that an electric charge was the analog of the magnetic bubble and that it could be stored on a tiny MOS capacitor.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] As it was fairly straightforward to fabricate a series of MOS capacitors in a row, they connected a suitable voltage to them so that the charge could be stepped along from one to the next.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This led to the invention of the charge-coupled device by Boyle and Smith in 1969.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] They conceived of the design of what they termed, in their notebook, "Charge 'Bubble' Devices".
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The initial paper describing the concept in April 1970 listed possible uses as memory, a delay line, and an imaging device.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The device could also be used as a shift register.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The essence of the design was the ability to transfer charge along the surface of a semiconductor from one storage capacitor to the next.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The first experimental device demonstrating the principle was a row of closely spaced metal squares on an oxidized silicon surface electrically accessed by wire bonds.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] It was demonstrated by Gil Amelio, Michael Francis Tompsett and George Smith in April 1970.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This was the first experimental application of the CCD in image sensor technology, and used a depleted MOS structure as the photodetector.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The first patent (U.S. patent 4,085,456) on the application of CCDs to imaging was assigned to Tompsett, who filed the application in 1971.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The first working CCD made with integrated circuit technology was a simple 8-bit shift register, reported by Tompsett, Amelio and Smith in August 1970.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This device had input and output circuits and was used to demonstrate its use as a shift register and as a crude eight pixel linear imaging device.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Development of the device progressed at a rapid rate.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] By 1971, Bell researchers led by Michael Tompsett were able to capture images with simple linear devices.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Several companies, including Fairchild Semiconductor, RCA and Texas Instruments, picked up on the invention and began development programs.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Fairchild's effort, led by ex-Bell researcher Gil Amelio, was the first with commercial devices, and by 1974 had a linear 500-element device and a 2D 100 × 100 pixel device.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Dillon, a scientist at Kodak Research Labs, invented the first color CCD image sensor by overlaying a color filter array on this Fairchild 100 x 100 pixel Interline CCD starting in 1974.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Steven Sasson, an electrical engineer working for the Kodak Apparatus Division, invented a digital still camera using this same Fairchild 100 × 100 CCD in 1975.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The interline transfer (ILT) CCD device was proposed by L.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Dyck at Fairchild in 1973 to reduce smear and eliminate a mechanical shutter.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] To further reduce smear from bright light sources, the frame-interline-transfer (FIT) CCD architecture was developed by K.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Kunii at Matsushita (now Panasonic) in 1981.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The first KH-11 KENNEN reconnaissance satellite equipped with charge-coupled device array (800 × 800 pixels) technology for imaging was launched in December 1976.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Under the leadership of Kazuo Iwama, Sony started a large development effort on CCDs involving a significant investment.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Eventually, Sony managed to mass-produce CCDs for their camcorders.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Before this happened, Iwama died in August 1982.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Subsequently, a CCD chip was placed on his tombstone to acknowledge his contribution.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The first mass-produced consumer CCD video camera, the CCD-G5, was released by Sony in 1983, based on a prototype developed by Yoshiaki Hagiwara in 1981.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Early CCD sensors suffered from shutter lag.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This was largely resolved with the invention of the pinned photodiode (PPD).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] It was invented by Nobukazu Teranishi, Hiromitsu Shiraki and Yasuo Ishihara at NEC in 1980.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] They recognized that lag can be eliminated if the signal carriers could be transferred from the photodiode to the CCD.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This led to their invention of the pinned photodiode, a photodetector structure with low lag, low noise, high quantum efficiency and low dark current.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] It was first publicly reported by Teranishi and Ishihara with A.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Arai in 1982, with the addition of an anti-blooming structure.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The new photodetector structure invented at NEC was given the name "pinned photodiode" (PPD) by B.C.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In 1987, the PPD began to be incorporated into most CCD devices, becoming a fixture in consumer electronic video cameras and then digital still cameras.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Since then, the PPD has been used in nearly all CCD sensors and then CMOS sensors.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In January 2006, Boyle and Smith were awarded the National Academy of Engineering Charles Stark Draper Prize, and in 2009 they were awarded the Nobel Prize for Physics for their invention of the CCD concept.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Michael Tompsett was awarded the 2010 National Medal of Technology and Innovation, for pioneering work and electronic technologies including the design and development of the first CCD imagers.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] He was also awarded the 2012 IEEE Edison Medal for "pioneering contributions to imaging devices including CCD Imagers, cameras and thermal imagers".
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In a CCD for capturing images, there is a photoactive region (an epitaxial layer of silicon), and a transmission region made out of a shift register (the CCD, properly speaking).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] An image is projected through a lens onto the capacitor array (the photoactive region), causing each capacitor to accumulate an electric charge proportional to the light intensity at that location.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] A one-dimensional array, used in line-scan cameras, captures a single slice of the image, whereas a two-dimensional array, used in video and still cameras, captures a two-dimensional picture corresponding to the scene projected onto the focal plane of the sensor.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Once the array has been exposed to the image, a control circuit causes each capacitor to transfer its contents to its neighbor (operating as a shift register).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The last capacitor in the array dumps its charge into a charge amplifier, which converts the charge into a voltage.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] By repeating this process, the controlling circuit converts the entire contents of the array in the semiconductor to a sequence of voltages.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Before the MOS capacitors are exposed to light, they are biased into the depletion region; in n-channel CCDs, the silicon under the bias gate is slightly *p*-doped or intrinsic.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The gate is then biased at a positive potential, above the threshold for strong inversion, which will eventually result in the creation of an *n* channel below the gate as in a MOSFET.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] However, it takes time to reach this thermal equilibrium: up to hours in high-end scientific cameras cooled at low temperature.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Initially after biasing, the holes are pushed far into the substrate, and no mobile electrons are at or near the surface; the CCD thus operates in a non-equilibrium state called deep depletion.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Then, when electron–hole pairs are generated in the depletion region, they are separated by the electric field, the electrons move toward the surface, and the holes move toward the substrate.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The last three processes are known as dark-current generation, and add noise to the image; they can limit the total usable integration time.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The accumulation of electrons at or near the surface can proceed either until image integration is over and charge begins to be transferred, or thermal equilibrium is reached.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In this case, the well is said to be full.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The maximum capacity of each well is known as the well depth, typically about 105 electrons per pixel.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] CCDs are normally susceptible to ionizing radiation and energetic particles which causes noise in the output of the CCD, and this must be taken into consideration in satellites using CCDs.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The photoactive region of a CCD is, generally, an epitaxial layer of silicon.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] It is lightly *p* doped (usually with boron) and is grown upon a substrate material, often p++.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In buried-channel devices, the type of design utilized in most modern CCDs, certain areas of the surface of the silicon are ion implanted with phosphorus, giving them an n-doped designation.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This region defines the channel in which the photogenerated charge packets will travel.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The gate oxide, i.e. the capacitor dielectric, is grown on top of the epitaxial layer and substrate.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Later in the process, polysilicon gates are deposited by chemical vapor deposition, patterned with photolithography, and etched in such a way that the separately phased gates lie perpendicular to the channels.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The channels are further defined by utilization of the LOCOS process to produce the channel stop region.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Channel stops are thermally grown oxides that serve to isolate the charge packets in one column from those in another.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] These channel stops are produced before the polysilicon gates are, as the LOCOS process utilizes a high-temperature step that would destroy the gate material.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The channel stops are parallel to, and exclusive of, the channel, or "charge carrying", regions.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Channel stops often have a p+ doped region underlying them, providing a further barrier to the electrons in the charge packets (this discussion of the physics of CCD devices assumes an electron transfer device, though hole transfer is possible).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The clocking of the gates, alternately high and low, will forward and reverse bias the diode that is provided by the buried channel (n-doped) and the epitaxial layer (p-doped).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This will cause the CCD to deplete, near the p–n junction and will collect and move the charge packets beneath the gates—and within the channels—of the device.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] CCD manufacturing and operation can be optimized for different uses.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The above process describes a frame transfer CCD.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] While CCDs may be manufactured on a heavily doped p++ wafer it is also possible to manufacture a device inside p-wells that have been placed on an n-wafer.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This second method, reportedly, reduces smear, dark current, and infrared and red response.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This method of manufacture is used in the construction of interline-transfer devices.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Another version of CCD is called a peristaltic CCD.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In a peristaltic charge-coupled device, the charge-packet transfer operation is analogous to the peristaltic contraction and dilation of the digestive system.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The peristaltic CCD has an additional implant that keeps the charge away from the silicon/silicon dioxide interface and generates a large lateral electric field from one gate to the next.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This provides an additional driving force to aid in transfer of the charge packets.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The CCD image sensors can be implemented in several different architectures.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The most common are full-frame, frame-transfer, and interline.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] These architectures differ primarily in their approach to the problem of shuttering.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In a full-frame device, all of the image area is active, and there is no electronic shutter.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] A mechanical shutter must be added to this type of sensor or the image smears as the device is clocked or read out.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] With a frame-transfer CCD, half of the silicon area is covered by an opaque mask (typically aluminum).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The image can be quickly transferred from the image area to the opaque area or storage region with acceptable smear of a few percent.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] That image can then be read out slowly from the storage region while a new image is integrating or exposing in the active area.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Frame-transfer devices typically do not require a mechanical shutter and were a common architecture for early solid-state broadcast cameras.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The downside to the frame-transfer architecture is that it requires twice the silicon real estate of an equivalent full-frame device; hence, it costs roughly twice as much.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The interline architecture extends this concept one step further and masks every other column of the image sensor for storage.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In this device, only one pixel shift has to occur to transfer from image area to storage area; thus, shutter times can be less than a microsecond and smear is essentially eliminated.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The advantage is not free, however, as the imaging area is now covered by opaque strips dropping the fill factor to approximately 50 percent and the effective quantum efficiency by an equivalent amount.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Modern designs have addressed this deleterious characteristic by adding microlenses on the surface of the device to direct light away from the opaque regions and on the active area.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Microlenses can bring the fill factor back up to 90 percent or more depending on pixel size and the overall system's optical design.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The choice of architecture comes down to one of utility.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] If the application cannot tolerate an expensive, failure-prone, or power-intensive mechanical shutter, an interline device may be the right choice.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Consumer snap-shot cameras have used interline devices.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] On the other hand, for those applications that require the best possible light collection, or where cost, power and time are less important, the full-frame device is the right choice.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Astronomers tend to prefer full-frame devices.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Frame-transfer is a middle compromise that was more common before the fill-factor issue of interline devices was addressed.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Today, frame-transfer is usually chosen when an interline architecture is not available, such as in a back-illuminated device.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] CCDs containing grids of pixels are used in digital cameras, optical scanners, and video cameras as light-sensing devices.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] They commonly respond to 70 percent of the incident light (meaning a quantum efficiency of about 70 percent) making them far more efficient than photographic film, which captures only about 2 percent of the incident light.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Most common types of CCDs are sensitive to near-infrared light, which allows infrared photography, night-vision devices, and zero lux (or near zero lux) video-recording/photography.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] For normal silicon-based detectors, the sensitivity is limited to 1.1 μm.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] One other consequence of their sensitivity to infrared is that infrared from remote controls often appears on CCD-based digital cameras or camcorders if they do not have infrared blockers.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Cooling reduces the array's dark current, improving the sensitivity of the CCD to low light intensities, even for ultraviolet and visible wavelengths.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Professional observatories often cool their detectors with liquid nitrogen to reduce the dark current, and therefore the thermal noise, to negligible levels.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The frame transfer CCD imager was the first imaging structure proposed for CCD Imaging by Michael Tompsett at Bell Laboratories.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] A **frame transfer CCD** is a specialized CCD, often used in astronomy and some professional video cameras, designed for high exposure efficiency and correctness.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The normal functioning of a CCD, astronomical or otherwise, can be divided into two phases: exposure and readout.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] During the first phase, the CCD passively collects incoming photons, storing electrons in its cells.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] After the exposure time is passed, the cells are read out one line at a time.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] During the readout phase, cells are shifted down the entire area of the CCD.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] While they are shifted, they continue to collect light.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Thus, if the shifting is not fast enough, errors can result from light that falls on a cell holding charge during the transfer.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] These errors are referred to as rolling shutter effect, making fast moving objects appear distorted.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In addition, the CCD cannot be used to collect light while it is being read out.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] A faster shifting requires a faster readout, and a faster readout can introduce errors in the cell charge measurement, leading to a higher noise level.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] A frame transfer CCD solves both problems: it has a shielded, not light sensitive, area containing as many cells as the area exposed to light.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Typically, this area is covered by a reflective material such as aluminium.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] When the exposure time is up, the cells are transferred very rapidly to the hidden area.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Here, safe from any incoming light, cells can be read out at any speed one deems necessary to correctly measure the cells' charge.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] At the same time, the exposed part of the CCD is collecting light again, so no delay occurs between successive exposures.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The disadvantage of such a CCD is the higher cost: the cell area is basically doubled, and more complex control electronics are needed.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] An intensified charge-coupled device (ICCD) is a CCD that is optically connected to an image intensifier that is mounted in front of the CCD.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] An image intensifier includes three functional elements: a photocathode, a micro-channel plate (MCP) and a phosphor screen.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] These three elements are mounted one close behind the other in the mentioned sequence.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The photons which are coming from the light source fall onto the photocathode, thereby generating photoelectrons.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The photoelectrons are accelerated towards the MCP by an electrical control voltage, applied between photocathode and MCP.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The electrons are multiplied inside of the MCP and thereafter accelerated towards the phosphor screen.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The phosphor screen finally converts the multiplied electrons back to photons which are guided to the CCD by a fiber optic or a lens.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] An image intensifier inherently includes a shutter functionality: If the control voltage between the photocathode and the MCP is reversed, the emitted photoelectrons are not accelerated towards the MCP but return to the photocathode.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Thus, no electrons are multiplied and emitted by the MCP, no electrons are going to the phosphor screen and no light is emitted from the image intensifier.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In this case no light falls onto the CCD, which means that the shutter is closed.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The process of reversing the control voltage at the photocathode is called *gating* and therefore ICCDs are also called gateable CCD cameras.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Besides the extremely high sensitivity of ICCD cameras, which enable single photon detection, the gateability is one of the major advantages of the ICCD over the EMCCD cameras.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The highest performing ICCD cameras enable shutter times as short as 200 picoseconds.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] ICCD cameras are in general somewhat higher in price than EMCCD cameras because they need the expensive image intensifier.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] On the other hand, EMCCD cameras need a cooling system to cool the EMCCD chip down to temperatures around 170 K (−103 °C).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This cooling system adds additional costs to the EMCCD camera and often yields heavy condensation problems in the application.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] ICCDs are used in night vision devices and in various scientific applications.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The gain register is split up into a large number of stages.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In each stage, the electrons are multiplied by impact ionization in a similar way to an avalanche diode.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The gain probability at every stage of the register is small (*P* < 2%), but as the number of elements is large (N > 500), the overall gain can be very high ( $g=(1+P)^{N}$ ), with single input electrons giving many thousands of output electrons.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Reading a signal from a CCD gives a noise background, typically a few electrons.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In an EMCCD, this noise is superimposed on many thousands of electrons rather than a single electron; the devices' primary advantage is thus their negligible readout noise.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The use of avalanche breakdown for amplification of photo charges had already been described in the U.S. patent 3,761,744 in 1973 by George E.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] EMCCDs show a similar sensitivity to intensified CCDs (ICCDs).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] However, as with ICCDs, the gain that is applied in the gain register is stochastic and the *exact* gain that has been applied to a pixel's charge is impossible to know.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] At high gains (> 30), this uncertainty has the same effect on the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) as halving the quantum efficiency (QE) with respect to operation with a gain of unity.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This effect is referred to as the *excess noise factor* (ENF).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] However, at very low light levels (where the quantum efficiency is most important), it can be assumed that a pixel either contains an electron—or not.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This removes the noise associated with the stochastic multiplication at the risk of counting multiple electrons in the same pixel as a single electron.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] To avoid multiple counts in one pixel due to coincident photons in this mode of operation, high frame rates are essential.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The dispersion in the gain is shown in the graph on the right.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] For very large numbers of input electrons, this complex distribution function converges towards a Gaussian.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Because of the lower costs and better resolution, EMCCDs are capable of replacing ICCDs in many applications.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] ICCDs still have the advantage that they can be gated very fast and thus are useful in applications like range-gated imaging.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] EMCCD cameras indispensably need a cooling system—using either thermoelectric cooling or liquid nitrogen—to cool the chip down to temperatures in the range of −65 to −95 °C (−85 to −139 °F).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This cooling system adds additional costs to the EMCCD imaging system and may yield condensation problems in the application.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] However, high-end EMCCD cameras are equipped with a permanent hermetic vacuum system confining the chip to avoid condensation issues.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The low-light capabilities of EMCCDs find use in astronomy and biomedical research, among other fields.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In terms of noise, commercial EMCCD cameras typically have clock-induced charge (CIC) and dark current (dependent on the extent of cooling) that together lead to an effective readout noise ranging from 0.01 to 1 electrons per pixel read.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] However, recent improvements in EMCCD technology have led to a new generation of cameras capable of producing significantly less CIC, higher charge transfer efficiency and an EM gain 5 times higher than what was previously available.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] These advances in low-light detection lead to an effective total background noise of 0.001 electrons per pixel read, a noise floor unmatched by any other low-light imaging device.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Thermal noise and cosmic rays may alter the pixels in the CCD array.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] To counter such effects, astronomers take several exposures with the CCD shutter closed and opened.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The average of images taken with the shutter closed is necessary to lower the random noise.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Once developed, the dark frame average image is then subtracted from the open-shutter image to remove the dark current and other systematic defects (dead pixels, hot pixels, etc.) in the CCD.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Newer Skipper CCDs counter noise by collecting data with the same collected charge multiple times and has applications in precision light dark matter searches and neutrino measurements.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The Hubble Space Telescope, in particular, has a highly developed series of steps ("data reduction pipeline") to convert the raw CCD data to useful images.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] CCD cameras used in astrophotography often require sturdy mounts to cope with vibrations from wind and other sources, along with the tremendous weight of most imaging platforms.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] To take long exposures of galaxies and nebulae, many astronomers use a technique known as auto-guiding.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Most autoguiders use a second CCD chip to monitor deviations during imaging.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This chip can rapidly detect errors in tracking and command the mount motors to correct for them.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] An unusual astronomical application of CCDs, called drift-scanning, uses a CCD to make a fixed telescope behave like a tracking telescope and follow the motion of the sky.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The charges in the CCD are transferred and read in a direction parallel to the motion of the sky, and at the same speed.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In this way, the telescope can image a larger region of the sky than its normal field of view.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The Sloan Digital Sky Survey is the most famous example of this, using the technique to produce a survey of over a quarter of the sky.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The Gaia space telescope is another instrument operating in this mode, rotating about its axis at a constant rate of 1 revolution in 6 hours and scanning a 360° by 0.5° strip on the sky during this time; a star traverses the entire focal plane in about 40 seconds (effective exposure time).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In addition to imagers, CCDs are also used in an array of analytical instrumentation including spectrometers and interferometers.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Digital color cameras, including the digital color cameras in smartphones, generally use an integral color image sensor, which has a color filter array fabricated on top of the monochrome pixels of the CCD.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The most popular CFA pattern is known as the Bayer filter, which is named for its inventor, Kodak scientist Bryce Bayer.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] In the Bayer pattern, each square of four pixels has one filtered red, one blue, and two green pixels (the human eye has greater acuity for luminance, which is more heavily weighted in green than in either red or blue).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] As a result, the luminance information is collected in each row and column using a checkerboard pattern, and the color resolution is lower than the luminance resolution.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Better color separation can be reached by three-CCD devices (3CCD) and a dichroic beam splitter prism, that splits the image into red, green and blue components.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Each of the three CCDs is arranged to respond to a particular color.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Many professional video camcorders, and some semi-professional camcorders, use this technique, although developments in competing CMOS technology have made CMOS sensors, both with beam-splitters and Bayer filters, increasingly popular in high-end video and digital cinema cameras.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Another advantage of 3CCD over a Bayer mask device is higher quantum efficiency (higher light sensitivity), because most of the light from the lens enters one of the silicon sensors, while a Bayer mask absorbs a high proportion (more than 2/3) of the light falling on each pixel location.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] For still scenes, for instance in microscopy, the resolution of a Bayer mask device can be enhanced by microscanning technology.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] During the process of color co-site sampling, several frames of the scene are produced.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Between acquisitions, the sensor is moved in pixel dimensions, so that each point in the visual field is acquired consecutively by elements of the mask that are sensitive to the red, green, and blue components of its color.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Eventually every pixel in the image has been scanned at least once in each color and the resolution of the three channels become equivalent (the resolutions of red and blue channels are quadrupled while the green channel is doubled).
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Sensors (CCD / CMOS) come in various sizes, or image sensor formats.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] These sizes are often referred to with an inch fraction designation such as 1/1.8″ or 2/3″ called the optical format.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] This measurement originates back in the 1950s and the time of Vidicon tubes.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] When a CCD exposure is long enough, eventually the electrons that collect in the "bins" in the brightest part of the image will overflow the bin, resulting in blooming.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] The structure of the CCD allows the electrons to flow more easily in one direction than another, resulting in vertical streaking.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Some anti-blooming features that can be built into a CCD reduce its sensitivity to light by using some of the pixel area for a drain structure.
[src:ccd-sensors/charge-coupled-device] Early developed a vertical anti-blooming drain that would not detract from the light collection area, and so did not reduce light sensitivity.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] The development of photodetectors began with the discovery of the photoelectric effect by Heinrich Hertz in 1887, later explained by Albert Einstein in 1905.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Early photodetectors, such as selenium cells invented in the late 19th century, were used in light meters and telegraph systems.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] The 1930s saw the invention of photomultiplier tubes, enabling the detection of faint light signals, which revolutionized fields like nuclear physics and astronomy.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] The mid-20th century brought semiconductor-based photodetectors, such as photodiodes and phototransistors, which transformed industries like telecommunications and computing.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Today, advancements continue with high-speed detectors and quantum technologies.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Photodetectors can be classified based on their mechanism of operation and device structure.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Photodetectors may be used in different configurations.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Single sensors may detect overall light levels.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] A 1-D array of photodetectors, as in a spectrophotometer or a Line scanner, may be used to measure the distribution of light along a line.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] A 2-D array of photodetectors may be used as an image sensor to form images from the pattern of light before it.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] A photodetector or array is typically covered by an illumination window, sometimes having an anti-reflective coating.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] **Photodiodes:** Photodiodes are the most common type of photodetectors.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] They are semiconductor devices with a PN junction.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Incident light generates electron-hole pairs in the depletion region of the junction, producing a photocurrent.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Photodiodes can be further categorized into: a.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] PIN Photodiodes: These photodiodes have an additional intrinsic (I) region between the P and N regions, which extends the depletion region and improves the device's performance. b.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Schottky Photodiodes: In Schottky photodiodes, a metal-semiconductor junction is used instead of a PN junction.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] They offer high-speed response and are commonly used in high-frequency applications.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] **Avalanche Photodiodes (APDs):** APDs are specialized photodiodes that incorporate avalanche multiplication.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] They have a high electric field region near the PN junction, which causes impact ionization and produces additional electron-hole pairs.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] This internal amplification improves the detection sensitivity.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] APDs are widely used in applications requiring high sensitivity, such as low-light imaging and long-distance optical communication.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] **Phototransistors:** Phototransistors are transistors with a light-sensitive base region.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Incident light causes a change in the base current, which controls the transistor's collector current.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Phototransistors offer amplification and can be used in applications that require both detection and signal amplification.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] **Charge-Coupled Devices (CCDs):** CCDs are imaging sensors composed of an array of tiny capacitors.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Incident light generates charge in the capacitors, which is sequentially read and processed to form an image.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] CCDs are commonly used in digital cameras and scientific imaging applications.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] **CMOS Image Sensors (CIS):** CMOS image sensors are based on complementary metal-oxide-semiconductor (CMOS) technology.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] They integrate photodetectors and signal processing circuitry on a single chip.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] CMOS image sensors have gained popularity due to their low power consumption, high integration, and compatibility with standard CMOS fabrication processes.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] **Photomultiplier Tubes (PMTs):** PMTs are vacuum tube-based photodetectors.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] They consist of a photocathode that emits electrons when illuminated, followed by a series of dynodes that multiply the electron current through secondary emission.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] PMTs offer high sensitivity and are used in applications that require low-light detection, such as particle physics experiments and scintillation detectors.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] These are some of the common photodetectors based on device structure.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Each type has its own characteristics, advantages, and applications in various fields, including imaging, communication, sensing, and scientific research.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] A graphene/n-type silicon heterojunction has been demonstrated to exhibit strong rectifying behavior and high photoresponsivity.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Graphene is coupled with silicon quantum dots (Si QDs) on top of bulk Si to form a hybrid photodetector.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Si QDs cause an increase of the built-in potential of the graphene/Si Schottky junction while reducing the optical reflection of the photodetector.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Both the electrical and optical contributions of Si QDs enable a superior performance of the photodetector.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Emerging applications include autonomous vehicles and quantum computing.
[src:ccd-sensors/photodetector] Future research focuses on improving sensitivity, reducing noise, and expanding wavelength detection ranges.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The **photoelectric effect** is the emission of electrons from a material caused by electromagnetic radiation such as ultraviolet light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Electrons emitted in this manner are called **photoelectrons**.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The phenomenon is studied in condensed matter physics, solid state, and quantum chemistry to draw inferences about the properties of atoms, molecules and solids.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The effect has found use in electronic devices specialized for light detection and precisely timed electron emission.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The experimental results disagree with classical electromagnetism, which predicts that continuous light waves transfer energy to electrons, which would then be emitted when they accumulate enough energy.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] An alteration in the intensity of light would theoretically change the kinetic energy of the emitted electrons, with sufficiently dim light resulting in a delayed emission.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The experimental results instead show that electrons are dislodged only when the light exceeds a certain frequency—regardless of the light's intensity or duration of exposure.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Emission of conduction electrons from typical metals requires a few electron-volt (eV) light quanta, corresponding to short-wavelength visible or ultraviolet light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In extreme cases, emissions are induced with photons approaching zero energy, like in systems with negative electron affinity and the emission from excited states, or a few hundred keV photons for core electrons in elements with a high atomic number.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Study of the photoelectric effect led to important steps in understanding the quantum nature of light and electrons and influenced the formation of the concept of wave–particle duality.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Other phenomena where light affects the movement of electric charges include the photoconductive effect, the photovoltaic effect, and the photoelectrochemical effect.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The photons of a light beam have a characteristic energy, called photon energy, which is proportional to the frequency of the light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In the photoemission process, when an electron within some material absorbs the energy of a photon and acquires more energy than its binding energy, it is likely to be ejected.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] If the photon energy is too low, the electron is unable to escape the material.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Since an increase in the intensity of low-frequency light will only increase the number of low-energy photons, this change in intensity will not create any single photon with enough energy to dislodge an electron.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Moreover, the energy of the emitted electrons will not depend on the intensity of the incoming light of a given frequency, but only on the energy of the individual photons.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] While free electrons can absorb any energy when irradiated as long as this is followed by an immediate re-emission, like in the Compton effect, in quantum systems all of the energy from one photon is absorbed—if the process is allowed by quantum mechanics—or none at all.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Part of the acquired energy is used to liberate the electron from its atomic binding, and the rest contributes to the electron's kinetic energy as a free particle.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Because electrons in a material occupy many different quantum states with different binding energies, and because they can sustain energy losses on their way out of the material, the emitted electrons will have a range of kinetic energies.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The electrons from the highest occupied states will have the highest kinetic energy.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In metals, those electrons will be emitted from the Fermi level.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] When the photoelectron is emitted into a solid rather than into a vacuum, the term *internal photoemission* is often used, and emission into a vacuum is distinguished as *external photoemission*.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Even though photoemission can occur from any material, it is most readily observed from metals and other conductors.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This is because the process produces a charge imbalance which, if not neutralized by current flow, results in the increasing potential barrier until the emission completely ceases.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The energy barrier to photoemission is usually increased by nonconductive oxide layers on metal surfaces, so most practical experiments and devices based on the photoelectric effect use clean metal surfaces in evacuated tubes.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Vacuum also helps observing the electrons since it prevents gases from impeding their flow between the electrodes.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Sunlight is an inconsistent and variable source of ultraviolet light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Cloud cover, ozone concentration, altitude, and surface reflection all alter the amount of UV.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Laboratory sources of UV are based on xenon arc lamps or, for more uniform but weaker light, fluorescent lamps.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] More specialized sources include ultraviolet lasers and synchrotron radiation.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The classical setup to observe the photoelectric effect includes a light source, a set of filters to monochromatize the light, a vacuum tube transparent to ultraviolet light, an emitting electrode (E) exposed to the light, and a collector (C) whose voltage *V*C can be externally controlled.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] A positive external voltage is used to direct the photoemitted electrons onto the collector.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] If the frequency and the intensity of the incident radiation are fixed, the photoelectric current *I* increases with an increase in the positive voltage, as more and more electrons are directed onto the electrode.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] When no additional photoelectrons can be collected, the photoelectric current attains a saturation value.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This current can only increase with the increase of the intensity of light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] An increasing negative voltage prevents all but the highest-energy electrons from reaching the collector.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] When no current is observed through the tube, the negative voltage has reached the value that is high enough to slow down and stop the most energetic photoelectrons of kinetic energy *K*max.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This value of the retarding voltage is called the *stopping potential* or *cut off* potential *V*o.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Since the work done by the retarding potential in stopping the electron of charge *e* is *eV*o, the following must hold *eV*o = *K*max.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The current-voltage curve is sigmoidal, but its exact shape depends on the experimental geometry and the electrode material properties.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] For a given metal surface, there exists a certain minimum frequency of incident radiation below which no photoelectrons are emitted.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This frequency is called the *threshold frequency*.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Increasing the frequency of the incident beam increases the maximum kinetic energy of the emitted photoelectrons, and the stopping voltage has to increase.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The number of emitted electrons may also change because the probability that each photon results in an emitted electron is a function of photon energy.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] For a given metal and frequency of incident radiation, the rate at which photoelectrons are ejected is directly proportional to the intensity of the incident light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The time lag between the incidence of radiation and the emission of a photoelectron is very small, less than 10−9 second.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Angular distribution of the photoelectrons is highly dependent on polarization (the direction of the electric field) of the incident light, as well as the emitting material's quantum properties such as atomic and molecular orbital symmetries and the electronic band structure of crystalline solids.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In materials without macroscopic order, the distribution of electrons tends to peak in the direction of polarization of linearly polarized light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The experimental technique that can measure these distributions to infer the material's properties is angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In 1905, Albert Einstein proposed a theory of the photoelectric effect using a concept that light consists of tiny packets of energy known as photons or light quanta.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Each packet carries energy $h\nu$ that is proportional to the frequency $\nu$ of the corresponding electromagnetic wave.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The proportionality constant h has become known as the Planck constant.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] It is called the work function of the surface and is sometimes denoted $\Phi$ or $\varphi$ .
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Kinetic energy is positive, and $\nu >\nu _{o}$ is required for the photoelectric effect to occur.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The frequency $\nu _{o}$ is the threshold frequency for the given material.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Einstein's formula, however simple, explained all the phenomenology of the photoelectric effect, and had far-reaching consequences in the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Electrons that are bound in atoms, molecules and solids each occupy distinct states of well-defined binding energies.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] When light quanta deliver more than this amount of energy to an individual electron, the electron may be emitted into free space with excess (kinetic) energy that is $h\nu$ higher than the electron's binding energy.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The distribution of kinetic energies thus reflects the distribution of the binding energies of the electrons in the atomic, molecular or crystalline system: an electron emitted from the state at binding energy $E_{B}$ is found at kinetic energy $E_{k}=h\nu -E_{B}$ .
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This distribution is one of the main characteristics of the quantum system, and can be used for further studies in quantum chemistry and quantum physics.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The electronic properties of ordered, crystalline solids are determined by the distribution of the electronic states with respect to energy and momentum—the electronic band structure of the solid.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Theoretical models of photoemission from solids show that this distribution is, for the most part, preserved in the photoelectric effect.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Electron propagation to the surface in which some electrons may be scattered because of interactions with other constituents of the solid.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Electrons that originate deeper in the solid are much more likely to suffer collisions and emerge with altered energy and momentum.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Their mean-free path is a universal curve dependent on electron's energy.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Electron escape through the surface barrier into free-electron-like states of the vacuum.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In this step the electron loses energy in the amount of the *work function of the surface*, and suffers from the momentum loss in the direction perpendicular to the surface.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] There are cases where the three-step model fails to explain peculiarities of the photoelectron intensity distributions.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The more elaborate *one-step model* treats the effect as a coherent process of photoexcitation into the final state of a finite crystal for which the wave function is free-electron-like outside of the crystal, but has a decaying envelope inside.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In 1839, Alexandre Edmond Becquerel discovered the related photovoltaic effect while studying the effect of light on electrolytic cells.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Though not equivalent to the photoelectric effect, his work on photovoltaics was instrumental in showing a strong relationship between light and electronic properties of materials.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In 1873, Willoughby Smith discovered photoconductivity in selenium while testing the metal for its high resistance properties in conjunction with his work involving submarine telegraph cables.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Johann Elster (1854–1920) and Hans Geitel (1855–1923), students in Heidelberg, investigated the effects produced by light on electrified bodies and developed the first practical photoelectric cells that could be used to measure the intensity of light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The order of the metals for this effect was the same as in Volta's series for contact-electricity, the most electropositive metals giving the largest photo-electric effect.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In 1887, Heinrich Hertz observed the photoelectric effect and reported on the production and reception of electromagnetic waves.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The receiver in his apparatus consisted of a coil with a spark gap, where a spark would be seen upon detection of electromagnetic waves.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] He placed the apparatus in a darkened box to see the spark better.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] However, he noticed that the maximum spark length was reduced when inside the box.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] A glass panel that was placed between the source of electromagnetic waves and the receiver absorbed ultraviolet radiation that assisted the electrons in jumping across the gap.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] When removed, the spark length would increase.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] He observed no decrease in spark length when he replaced the glass with quartz, as quartz does not absorb UV radiation.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The discoveries by Hertz led to a series of investigations by Wilhelm Hallwachs, Hoor, Augusto Righi and Aleksander Stoletov on the effect of light, and especially of ultraviolet light, on charged bodies.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Hallwachs connected a zinc plate to an electroscope.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] He allowed ultraviolet light to fall on a freshly cleaned zinc plate and observed that the zinc plate became uncharged if initially negatively charged, positively charged if initially uncharged, and more positively charged if initially positively charged.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] From these observations he concluded that some negatively charged particles were emitted by the zinc plate when exposed to ultraviolet light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] With regard to the *Hertz effect*, the researchers from the start showed the complexity of the phenomenon of photoelectric fatigue—the progressive diminution of the effect observed upon fresh metallic surfaces.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] According to Hallwachs, ozone played an important part in the phenomenon, and the emission was influenced by oxidation, humidity, and the degree of polishing of the surface.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] It was at the time unclear whether fatigue is absent in a vacuum.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In the period from 1888 until 1891, a detailed analysis of the photoeffect was performed by Aleksandr Stoletov with results reported in six publications.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Stoletov invented a new experimental setup which was more suitable for a quantitative analysis of the photoeffect.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] He discovered a direct proportionality between the intensity of light and the induced photoelectric current (the first law of photoeffect or Stoletov's law).
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Many substances besides metals discharge negative electricity under the action of ultraviolet light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Knoblauch compiled a list of these substances.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Thomson investigated ultraviolet light in Crookes tubes.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Thomson deduced that the ejected particles, which he called corpuscles, were of the same nature as cathode rays.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] These particles later became known as the electrons.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Thomson enclosed a metal plate (a cathode) in a vacuum tube, and exposed it to high-frequency radiation.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] It was thought that the oscillating electromagnetic fields caused the atoms' field to resonate and, after reaching a certain amplitude, caused subatomic corpuscles to be emitted, and current to be detected.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The amount of this current varied with the intensity and color of the radiation.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Larger radiation intensity or frequency would produce more current.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] During the years 1886–1902, Wilhelm Hallwachs and Philipp Lenard investigated the phenomenon of photoelectric emission in detail.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Lenard observed that a current flows through an evacuated glass tube enclosing two electrodes when ultraviolet radiation falls on one of them.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] As soon as ultraviolet radiation is stopped, the current also stops.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This initiated the concept of photoelectric emission.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The discovery of the ionization of gases by ultraviolet light was made by Philipp Lenard in 1900.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] As the effect was produced across several centimeters of air and yielded a greater number of positive ions than negative, it was natural to interpret the phenomenon, as J.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Thomson did, as a *Hertz effect* upon the particles present in the gas.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In 1902, Lenard observed that the energy of individual emitted electrons was independent of the applied light intensity.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This appeared to be at odds with Maxwell's wave theory of light, which predicted that the electron energy would be proportional to the intensity of the radiation.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Lenard observed the variation in electron energy with light frequency using a powerful electric arc lamp which enabled him to investigate large changes in intensity.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] However, Lenard's results were qualitative rather than quantitative because of the difficulty in performing the experiments: the experiments needed to be done on freshly cut metal so that the pure metal was observed, but it oxidized in a matter of minutes even in the partial vacuums he used.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The current emitted by the surface was determined by the light's intensity, or brightness: doubling the intensity of the light doubled the number of electrons emitted from the surface.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Initial investigation of the photoelectric effect in gasses by Lenard were followed up by J.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Thomson and then more decisively by Frederic Palmer Jr.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The gas photoemission was studied and showed very different characteristics than those at first attributed to it by Lenard.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In 1900, while studying black-body radiation, the German physicist Max Planck suggested in his "On the Law of Distribution of Energy in the Normal Spectrum" paper that the energy carried by electromagnetic waves could only be released in *packets* of energy.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In 1905, Albert Einstein published a paper advancing the hypothesis that light energy is carried in discrete quantized packets to explain experimental data from the photoelectric effect.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Einstein theorized that the energy in each quantum of light was equal to the frequency of light multiplied by a constant, later called the Planck constant.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] A photon above a threshold frequency has the required energy to eject a single electron, creating the observed effect.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This was a step in the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Millikan's highly accurate measurements of the Planck constant from the photoelectric effect supported Einstein's model, even though a corpuscular theory of light was for Millikan, at the time, "quite unthinkable".
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Einstein was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics for "his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect", and Millikan was awarded the Nobel Prize in 1923 for "his work on the elementary charge of electricity and on the photoelectric effect".
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Albert Einstein's mathematical description of how the photoelectric effect was caused by absorption of quanta of light was in one of his Annus Mirabilis papers, named "On a Heuristic Viewpoint Concerning the Production and Transformation of Light".
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The paper proposed a simple description of *energy quanta*, and showed how they explained the blackbody radiation spectrum.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] His explanation in terms of absorption of discrete quanta of light agreed with experimental results.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] It explained why the energy of photoelectrons was not dependent on incident light *intensity*.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This was a theoretical leap, but the concept was strongly resisted at first because it contradicted the wave theory of light that followed naturally from James Clerk Maxwell's equations of electromagnetism, and more generally, the assumption of infinite divisibility of energy in physical systems.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Einstein's work predicted that the energy of individual ejected electrons increases linearly with the frequency of the light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The precise relationship had not at that time been tested.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] By 1905 it was known that the energy of photoelectrons increases with increasing *frequency* of incident light and is independent of the *intensity* of the light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] However, the manner of the increase was not experimentally determined until 1914 when Millikan showed that Einstein's prediction was correct.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In 1937, the Bulgarian physicist Georgi Nadjakov discovered the *photoelectret state* in dielectrics.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The phenomenon is related to photoelectric effects in solids and later contributed to the physical basis of xerography.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The photoelectric effect helped to propel the then-emerging concept of wave–particle duality in the nature of light.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Light simultaneously possesses the characteristics of both waves and particles, each being manifested according to the circumstances.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The effect was impossible to understand in terms of the classical wave description of light, as the energy of the emitted electrons did not depend on the intensity of the incident radiation.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Classical theory predicted that the electrons would 'gather up' energy over a period of time, and then be emitted.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The quantum of light was given its modern name by Gilbert N.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Lewis when he coined the term 'photon' in his letter "The Conservation of Photons" to *Nature* published in 18 December 1926.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Research in recent years on the photoelectric effect has been focused on measurements on emission time of photoelectrons.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] For long, it was believed that photoemission is an instantaneous process.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] However, a seminal role in this field was played by experimental techniques on attosecond generation of pulses of light for studies on electron dynamics, which was recognised through the 2023 Nobel Prize in physics to Pierre Agostini, Ferenc Krausz and Anne L'Huillier.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] For example, in 2010, it was discovered that electron emission takes 20 attoseconds and that photoemission is associated with complex multielectron correlations and is not a single-electron process.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In a more recent work in the context of tungsten, measurements on photoelectron emission indicated that around 100 attoseconds are required to liberate an electron.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In another research, the value was found to be 45 attoseconds.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] A broad consensus is emerging towards the fact that photoemission is not instantaneous and involves finite time.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The role of electric field in photoelectric effect has also been empirically studied and it was found that electromagnetic radiation with a specific orientation of electric field can excite electrons leading to enhanced emission in the Terahertz range.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] These are extremely light-sensitive vacuum tubes with a coated photocathode inside the envelope.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The photo cathode contains combinations of materials such as cesium, rubidium, and antimony specially selected to provide a low work function, so when illuminated even by very low levels of light, the photocathode readily releases electrons.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] By means of a series of electrodes (dynodes) at ever-higher potentials, these electrons are accelerated and substantially increased in number through secondary emission to provide a readily detectable output current.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Photomultipliers are still commonly used wherever low levels of light must be detected.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Video camera tubes in the early days of television used the photoelectric effect.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] For example, Philo Farnsworth's "Image dissector" used a screen charged by the photoelectric effect to transform an optical image into a scanned electronic signal.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The distribution of electron energies is valuable for studying quantum properties of these systems.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] It can also be used to determine the elemental composition of the samples.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] For solids, the kinetic energy and emission angle distribution of the photoelectrons is measured for the complete determination of the electronic band structure in terms of the allowed binding energies and momenta of the electrons.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Modern instruments for angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy are capable of measuring these quantities with a precision better than 1 meV and 0.1°.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Photoelectron spectroscopy measurements are usually performed in a high-vacuum environment, because the electrons would be scattered by gas molecules if they were present.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] However, some companies are now selling products that allow photoemission in air.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The light source can be a laser, a discharge tube, or a synchrotron radiation source.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The concentric hemispherical analyzer is a typical electron energy analyzer.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] It uses an electric field between two hemispheres to change (disperse) the trajectories of incident electrons depending on their kinetic energies.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Photons hitting a thin film of alkali metal or semiconductor material such as gallium arsenide in an image intensifier tube cause the ejection of photoelectrons due to the photoelectric effect.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] These are accelerated by an electrostatic field where they strike a phosphor coated screen, converting the electrons back into photons.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Intensification of the signal is achieved either through acceleration of the electrons or by increasing the number of electrons through secondary emissions, such as with a micro-channel plate.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Sometimes a combination of both methods is used.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Additional kinetic energy is required to move an electron out of the conduction band and into the vacuum level.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This is known as the electron affinity of the photocathode and is another barrier to photoemission other than the forbidden band, explained by the band gap model.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Some materials such as gallium arsenide have an effective electron affinity that is below the level of the conduction band.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] In these materials, electrons that move to the conduction band all have sufficient energy to be emitted from the material, so the film that absorbs photons can be quite thick.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] These materials are known as negative electron affinity materials.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The photoelectric effect will cause spacecraft exposed to sunlight to develop a positive charge.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This can be a major problem, as other parts of the spacecraft are in shadow which will result in the spacecraft developing a negative charge from nearby plasmas.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The imbalance can discharge through delicate electrical components.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The static charge created by the photoelectric effect is self-limiting, because a higher charged object does not give up its electrons as easily as a lower charged object does.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Light from the Sun hitting lunar dust causes it to become positively charged from the photoelectric effect.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The charged dust then repels itself and lifts off the surface of the Moon by electrostatic levitation.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This manifests itself almost like an "atmosphere of dust", visible as a thin haze and blurring of distant features, and visible as a dim glow after the sun has set.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] This was first photographed by the Surveyor program probes in the 1960s, and most recently the Chang'e 3 rover observed dust deposition on lunar rocks as high as about 28 cm.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] It is thought that the smallest particles are repelled kilometers from the surface and that the particles move in "fountains" as they charge and discharge.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The probability of the photoelectric effect occurring is measured by the cross section of the interaction, which the atomic number of the target atom and photon energy.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Here *Z* is the atomic number and *n* is a number which varies between 4 and 5.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] The photoelectric effect rapidly decreases in significance in the gamma-ray region of the spectrum, with increasing photon energy.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] It is also more likely from elements with high atomic number.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Consequently, high-*Z* materials make good gamma-ray shields, which is the principal reason why lead (*Z* = 82) is preferred and most widely used.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] These cross-sections vary with the atomic number of the element that dominates the material and with the energy of the photons.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] As photon energies increase above those of a materials K-edge the probability of photoelectric interactions decreases and Compton scattering begins to dominate.
[src:ccd-sensors/photoelectric-effect] Above photon energies of 1.022 MeV, pair production begins, increasing rapidly with photon energy.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] A photodetector's responsivity is usually expressed in units of amperes or volts per watt of incident radiant power.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] For a system that responds linearly to its input, there is a unique responsivity.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] For nonlinear systems, the responsivity is the local slope.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] Many common photodetectors respond linearly as a function of the incident power.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] Responsivity is a function of the wavelength of the incident radiation and of the sensor's properties, such as the bandgap of the material of which the photodetector is made.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] where $\eta$ is the quantum efficiency (the conversion efficiency of photons to electrons) of the detector for a given wavelength, q is the electron charge, f is the frequency of the optical signal, and h is the Planck constant.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] This expression is also given in terms of $\lambda$ , the wavelength of the optical signal, and has the unit of amperes per watt (A/W).
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] The term responsivity is also used to summarize input–output relationship in non-electrical systems.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] For example, a neuroscientist may measure how neurons in the visual pathway respond to light.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] In this case, responsivity summarizes the change in the neural response per unit signal strength.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] The responsivity in these applications can have a variety of units.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] The signal strength typically is controlled by varying either intensity (intensity-response function) or contrast (contrast-response function).
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] The neural response measure depends on the part of the nervous system under study.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] For example, at the level of the retinal cones, the response might be in photocurrent.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] In the central nervous system the response is usually spikes per second.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] In functional neuroimaging, the response measure is usually BOLD contrast.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] The responsivity units reflect the relevant stimulus and physiological units.
[src:ccd-sensors/responsivity] When describing an amplifier, the more common term is gain.
